# **Mindset Shift 2: Turning Failure from Your Foe to Your Friend**

# **Failure Can Be Your Friend\!**

For most of my life I tied my self-worth to my performance. As one of the most driven students in my high school, I set records for the amount of work a student could get done in a year. Because of this, I completed high school in three years.

Looking back, I'm not entirely proud of my reputation because I see what motivated me. Most likely, people saw me as an extraordinary example of a hardworking young man. If they saw the downside, they certainly never told me.

The truth was I hated to fail or any appearance of failure.

I hated my music class because I couldn't get an A. Getting a B was below my dignity.

I was thrown completely off kilter if I publicly failed or got embarrassed. I did everything in my power to avoid making those kinds of mistakes. As a result, I played it safe.

## **The Liberating Benefits of Failure**

It took years for me to unhitch my self-worth from my performance; to give myself the grace and courage I needed to fail. Thankfully, it gets easier every day.

Why?

Because I now know failure doesn't have to be the end of the story.

I’ve discovered that failure is one of the best teachers of all times. It teaches you lessons you would not be able to learn any other way. It's a badge of honor: proof you were in the middle of the fight, trying to do something meaningful, while others watched idly by.

Best of all, failure does not mean you are a failure. My identity is not defined by my successes or my failures, which is why I can embrace failure.

Until you accept this truth, you will find yourself always running away from your fears, avoiding risk and potential setbacks.

You must see failure as a friend as something to embrace.
